<section xml:id="section-absolute-value-equations">
  <title>Absolute Value Equations</title>
  <objectives>
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-solve-absolute-value-equations" text="local">MTH 95 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Whether it's a washer, nut, bolt,
      or gear, when a machine part is made,
      it must be made to fit with all of the other parts of the system.
      Since no manufacturing process is perfect,
      there are small deviations from the norm when each piece is made.
      In fact, manufacturers have a <em>range</em>
      of acceptable values for each measurement of every screw,
      bolt, etc.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLfPh0EsBc0yLxr9gbK4dvy688zkCvMRi7" />
    </figure>

    <p>
      Let's say we were examining some new bolts just out of the factory.
      The manufacturer specifies that each bolt should be within a <em>tolerance</em> of
      <quantity>
        <mag>0.04</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>
      to
      <quantity>
        <mag>10</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>
      in diameter.
      So the lowest diameter that the bolt could be to make it through quality assurance is
      <quantity>
        <mag>0.04</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>
      smaller than
      <quantity>
        <mag>10</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>, which is
      <quantity>
        <mag>9.96</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>.
      Similarly, the largest diameter that the bolt could be is
      <quantity>
        <mag>0.04</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>
      larger than
      <quantity>
        <mag>10</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>, which is
      <quantity>
        <mag>10.04</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>.
    </p>

    <p>
      To write an equation that describes the minimum and maximum deviation from average,
      we want the difference between the actual diameter and the specification to be <!-- less than or  -->equal to
      <quantity>
        <mag>0.04</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>.
      Since absolute values are used to describe distances,
      we can summarize our thoughts mathematically as <m>\abs{x-10}=0.04</m>,
      where <m>x</m> represents the diameter of an acceptably sized bolt,
      in millimeters. This equation says the same thing as
      the lowest diameter that the bolt could be to make it through quality assurance is
      <quantity>
        <mag>9.96</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>
      and the largest diameter that the bolt could be is
      <quantity>
        <mag>10.04</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>.
      <!-- Since the minimum value is
      <quantity>
        <mag>9.96</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>
      and the maximum value is
      <quantity>
        <mag>10.04</mag><unit base="meter" prefix="milli" />
      </quantity>,
      our range of acceptable values should be <m>9.96 \le x \le 10.04</m> -->
    </p>

    <p>
      In this section we will examine a variety of problems <!-- and applications --> that relate to this sort of math with absolute values.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <subsection permid="RCb">
    <title>Graphs of Absolute Value Functions</title>
    <p permid="BJw">
      Absolute value functions have generally the same shape.
      They are usually described as <q>V</q>-shaped graphs and the tip of the <q>V</q>
      is called the <term>vertex</term>.
          <idx><h>vertex</h></idx>
      A few graphs of various absolute value functions are shown in <xref ref="figure-absolute-value">Figure</xref>.
      In general, the domain of an absolute value function
      (where there is a polynomial inside the absolute value)
      is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
    </p>

