    <p>
      We can solve absolute value equations graphically.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-absolute-value-solving-intro">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equations graphically using the graphs provided.

          <ol label="a." cols="2">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{x}=3</m>
              </p>

              <sidebyside widths="90%">

                <image>
                  <description>A Cartesian graph with the graph of y=abs(x);the graph has a V shape with the vertex of the V at the origin;the line on the right side has a slope of 1;the line on the left side has a slope of -1</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-6, xmax=6, ymin=-2, ymax=6, xtick={-5,-4,...,5}, ytick={-1,0,...,5}]
                    \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-6:6] {abs(x)} node[pos=0.65, sloped, below]{$y=\abs{x}$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
                </image>

              </sidebyside>

            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{2x+3}=5</m>
              </p>

              <sidebyside widths="90%">

                <image>
                  <description>A Cartesian graph with the graph of y=abs(x);the vertex of the V shape is at the point (-1.5,0);the line on the right side has a slope of 2 and the left side extends with slope -2.</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-6, xmax=6, ymin=-2, ymax=6, xtick={-5,-4,...,5}, ytick={-1,0,...,5}]
                    \addplot[secondcurve] coordinates {(-4.5,6) (-1.5,0) (1.5,6)} node[below,sloped,pos=0.25] {$y=\abs{2x+3}$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
                </image>

              </sidebyside>

            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To solve the equations graphically,
          first we need to graph the right sides of the equations also.

          <ol label="a." cols="2">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{x}=3</m>
              </p>

              <sidebyside widths="90%">

                <image>
                  <description>A Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(x) and y=3;the vertex of the V shape is at the origin. The right side has a slope of 1 and the left side has a slope of -1;the graph of y=3 is a horizontal line at y=3;the two graphs intersect at (-3,3) and (3,3)</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-6, xmax=6, ymin=-2, ymax=6, xtick={-5,-4,...,5}, ytick={-1,0,...,5}]
                    \addplot[firstcurve, domain=-6:6] {abs(x)} node[pos=0.65, sloped, below]{$y=\abs{x}$};
                    \addplot[thirdcurve, domain=-6:6] {3} node[pos=0.1, below]{$y=3$};
                    \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-3, 3)};
                    \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(3, 3)};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
                </image>

              </sidebyside>

              <p>
                Since the graph of <m>y=\abs{x}</m> crosses <m>y=3</m> at the <m>x</m>-values <m>-3</m> and <m>3</m>,
                the solution set to the equation
                <m>\abs{x}=3</m> must be <m>\{-3,3\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{2x+3}=5</m>
              </p>

              <sidebyside widths="90%">

                <image>
                  <description>A Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(2x+3) and y=5;the vertex of the V shape is at the point (-1.5,0);the right side has a slope of 2 and the left side has a slope of -2;the graph of y=5 is a horizontal line at y=5;the two graphs intersect at (-4,5) and (1,5)</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-6, xmax=6, ymin=-2, ymax=6, xtick={-5,-4,...,5}, ytick={-1,-0,...,5}]
                    \addplot[secondcurve] coordinates {(-4.5,6) (-1.5,0) (1.5,6)} node[below,sloped,pos=0.25] {$y=\abs{2x+3}$};
                    \addplot[thirdcurve, domain=-6:6] {5} node[pos=0.9, below]{$y=5$};
                    \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-4, 5)};
                    \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(1, 5)};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
                </image>

              </sidebyside>

              <p>
                Since the graph of <m>y=\abs{2x+3}</m> crosses <m>y=5</m> at the <m>x</m>-values <m>-4</m> and <m>1</m>,
                the solution set to the equation
                <m>\abs{2x+3}=5</m> must be <m>\{-4,1\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        Please note that there is a big difference between the expression <m>\abs{3}</m> and the equation <m>\abs{x}=3</m>.

        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The expression <m>\abs{3}</m> is describing the distance from <m>0</m> to the number <m>3</m>.
              The distance is just <m>3</m>.
              So <m>\abs{3}=3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The equation <m>\abs{x}=3</m> is asking you to find the numbers that are a distance of <m>3</m> from <m>0</m>.
              These two numbers are <m>3</m> and <m>-3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </remark>

    <p>
      Let's solve some absolute value equations algebraically.
      To motivate this,
      we will think about what an absolute value equation means in terms of the
      <q>distance from zero</q>
      definition of absolute value.
      If
      <me>
        \abs{X}=n
      </me>,
      where <m>n\ge0</m>, then this means that we want all of the numbers,
      <m>X</m>, that are a distance <m>n</m> from <m>0</m>.
      Since we can only go left or right along the number line,
      this is describing both <m>X=n</m> as well as <m>X=-n</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-absolute-value-solving-algebraically-explanation">
      <caption>A Numberline with Points a Distance <m>n</m> from <m>0</m></caption>
      <image width="47%">
        <description>a number line graph with a point labeled at n and -n;both points are n units from 0</description>

               <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[numberline, xmin=-5, xmax=5, xtick={0}, minor xtick={-5,-4,...,5}, xlabel={$X$},width=0.47\linewidth]
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates{(4,0)} node[below]{$n$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates{(-4,0)} node[below]{$-n$};
                    \addplot[|-|, dashed, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,0.4) (4,0.4)} node[above, pos=0.5]{$n$ units};
                    \addplot[|-|, dashed, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,0.4) (-4,0.4)} node[above, pos=0.5]{$n$ units};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
      </image>

    </figure>

    <p>
      Let's summarize this.
    </p>

    <fact xml:id="fact-absolute-value-equation-i">
      <title>Equations with an Absolute Value Expression</title>
      <idx><h>absolute value</h><h>solving equations with one absolute value</h></idx>
      <idx><h>solving</h><h>absolute value equations</h><h>with one absolute value</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>n</m> be a non-negative number and <m>X</m> be an algebraic expression.
          Then the equation
          <me>
            \abs{X}=n
          </me>
          has the same solutions as
          <me>
            X=n\text{ or } X=-n
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the absolute value equations using <xref ref="fact-absolute-value-equation-i">Fact</xref>.
          Write solutions in a solution set.

          <ol label="a." cols="3">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{x}=6</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{x}=-4</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{5x-7}=23</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{14-3x}=8</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\abs{3-4x}=0</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <xref ref="fact-absolute-value-equation-i">Fact</xref>
                says that the equation <m>\abs{x}=6</m> is the same as
                <me>
                  x=6\text{ or } x=-6
                </me>.
                Thus the solution set is <m>\{6,-6\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <xref ref="fact-absolute-value-equation-i">Fact</xref>
                doesn't actually apply to the equation
                <m>\abs{x}=-4</m> because the value on the right side is <em>negative</em>.
                How often is an absolute value of a number negative?
                Never!
                Thus, there are no solutions and the solution set is the empty set,
                denoted <m>\emptyset</m>. <idx><h>empty set</h></idx>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\abs{5x-7}=23</m> breaks into two pieces,
                each of which needs to be solved independently.
                <md>
                  <mrow>5x-7\amp=23\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 5x-7\amp=-23</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>5x-7\addright{7}\amp=23\addright{7}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 5x-7\addright{7}\amp=-23\addright{7}</mrow> -->
                  <mrow>5x\amp=30\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 5x\amp=-16</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>\divideunder{5x}{5}\amp=\divideunder{30}{5}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp \divideunder{5x}{5}\amp=-\divideunder{16}{5}</mrow> -->
                  <mrow>x\amp=6\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-\frac{16}{5}</mrow>
                </md>
                Thus the solution set is <m>\left\{6,-\frac{16}{5}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\abs{14-3x}=8</m> breaks into two pieces,
                each of which needs to be solved independently.
                <md>
                  <mrow>14-3x\amp=8\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 14-3x\amp=-8</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>14-3x\subtractright{14}\amp=8\subtractright{14}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 14-3x\subtractright{14}\amp=-8\subtractright{14}</mrow> -->
                  <mrow>-3x\amp=-6\amp\amp\text{or}\amp -3x\amp=-22</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>\divideunder{-3x}{-3}\amp=\divideunder{-6}{-3}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp \divideunder{-3x}{-3}\amp=\divideunder{-22}{-3}</mrow> -->
                  <mrow>x\amp=2\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{22}{3}</mrow>
                </md>
                Thus the solution set is <m>\left\{2,\frac{22}{3}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\abs{3-4x}=0</m> breaks into two pieces,
                each of which needs to be solved independently.
                <md>
                  <mrow>3-4x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 3-4x\amp=-0</mrow>
                  <intertext>Since these are identical equations, all we have to do is solve one equation.</intertext>
                  <mrow>3-4x\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>-4x\amp=-3</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{3}{4}</mrow>
                </md>
                Thus, the equation <m>\abs{3-4x}=0</m> only has one solution,
                and the solution set is <m>\left\{\frac{3}{4}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Absolute Value Equations with Two Absolute Values</title>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let's graphically solve an equation with an absolute value expression on each side: <m>\abs{x}=\abs{2x+6}</m>.
          Since <m>\abs{x}=3</m> had two solutions as we saw in <xref ref="example-absolute-value-solving-intro">Example</xref>,
          you might be wondering how many solutions <m>\abs{x}=\abs{2x+6}</m> will have.
          Make a graph to find out what the solutions of the equation are.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <figure xml:id="figure-absolute-value-solving-part-ii-intro">
        <caption><m>y=\abs{x}</m> and <m>y=\abs{2x+6}</m></caption>
        <image width="47%">
          <description>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(x) and y=abs(2x+6);y=abs(x) has its vertex at (0,0) with a slope of 1 on the right and -1 on the left;y=abs(2x+6) has its vertex at (-3,0) with a slope of 2 on the right and -2 on the left;the V-shaped graphs cross at the points (-2,2) and (-6,6)</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-8, xmax=4, ymin=-2, ymax=8, xtick={-6,-4,...,2}, ytick={-1,0,...,7},width=0.47\linewidth]
                    \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(-7,8) (-3,0) (1,8)} node[pos=0.25, sloped, below] {$y=\abs{2x+6}$};
                    \addplot[secondcurve] coordinates {(-8,8) (0,0) (4,4)} node[pos=0.83, sloped, above] {$y=\abs{x}$};
                    \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-2, 2)};
                    \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-6, 6)};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
        </image>

        </figure>

        <p>
          <xref ref="figure-absolute-value-solving-part-ii-intro">Figure</xref>
          shows that there are also two points of intersection between the graphs of
          <m>y=\abs{x}</m> and <m>y=\abs{2x+6}</m>.
          The solutions to the equation
          <m>\abs{x}=\abs{2x+6}</m> are the <m>x</m>-values where the graphs cross.
          So, the solution set is <m>\{-6,-2\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equation <m>\abs{x+1}=\abs{2x-4}</m> graphically.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            First break up the equation into the left side and the right side and graph each separately,
            as in <m>y=\abs{x+1}</m> and <m>y=\abs{2x-4}</m>.
            We can see in the graph that the graphs intersect twice.
            The <m>x</m>-values of those intersections are <m>1</m> and <m>5</m> so the solution set to the equation <m>\abs{x+1}=\abs{2x-4}</m> is <m>\{1,5\}</m>.
          </p>

          <figure>
            <caption><m>y=\abs{x+1}</m> and <m>y=\abs{2x-4}</m></caption>
            <image width="47%">
              <description>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(x+1) and y=abs(2x-4);y=abs(x+1) has its vertex at (-1,0) with a slope of 1 on the right and -1 on the left;y=abs(2x-4) has its vertex at (2,0) with a slope of 2 on the right and -2 on the left;the V-shaped graphs cross at the points (1,2) and (5,6)</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[xmin=-3, xmax=7, ymin=-1, ymax=8, xtick={-2,-1,...,6}, ytick={1,2,...,7}, minor ytick={-1,0,...,8}]
                    \addplot+[domain=-2:6, samples=99] {abs(2*x-4)} node[pos=0.1, sloped, below]{$y=\abs{2x-4}$};
                    \addplot+[domain=-3:7, samples=99] {abs(x+1)} node[pos=0.6, sloped, above]{$y=\abs{x+1}$};
                    \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(1, 2)};
                    \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(5, 6)};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      Fortunately, this kind of equation also has a rule  to solve these types of equations algebraically that is similar to the <xref ref="fact-absolute-value-equation-i" text="custom">rule for equations with one absolute value</xref>.
    </p>

    <fact xml:id="fact-absolute-value-equation-ii">
      <title>Equations with Two Absolute Value Expressions</title>
      <idx><h>absolute value</h><h>solving equations with two absolute values</h></idx>
      <idx><h>solving</h><h>absolute value equations</h><h>with two absolute values</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be linear algebraic expressions.
          Then, the equation
          <me>
            \abs{X}=\abs{Y}
          </me>
          has the same solutions as
          <me>
            X=Y\text{ or } X=-Y
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <remark>
      <p>
        You might wonder why the negative sign <q>has</q>
        to go on the right side of the equation in <m>X=-Y</m>.
        It doesn't; it can go on either side of the equation.
        The equations <m>X=-Y</m> and <m>-X=Y</m> are equivalent.
        Similarly, <m>-X=-Y</m> is equivalent to <m>X=Y</m>.
        That's why we only need to solve two of the four possible equations.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equations using <xref ref="fact-absolute-value-equation-ii">Fact</xref>.

          <ol label="a." cols="2">
            <li><m>\abs{x-4}=\abs{3x-2}</m></li>

            <li><m>\abs{\frac{1}{2}x+1}=\abs{\frac{1}{3}x+2}</m></li>

            <li><m>\abs{x-2}=\abs{x+1}</m></li>

            <li><m>\abs{x-1}=\abs{1-x}</m></li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\abs{x-4}=\abs{3x-2}</m> breaks down into two pieces:
                <md>
                  <mrow>x-4\amp=3x-2\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-4\amp=-(3x-2)</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-4\amp=3x-2\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-4\amp=\highlight{-3x+2}</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>x-4\addright{2}\subtractright{x}\amp=3x-2\addright{2}\subtractright{x}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp \addleft{3x}x-4\addright{4}\amp=\addleft{3x}-3x+2\addright{4}</mrow> -->
                  <mrow>-2\amp=2x\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 4x\amp=6</mrow>
                  <mrow>\divideunder{-2}{2}\amp=\divideunder{2x}{2}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp \divideunder{4x}{4}\amp=\divideunder{6}{4}</mrow>
                  <mrow>-1\amp=x\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                So, the solution set is <m>\left\{-1,\frac{3}{2}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            <!-- todo: add a verification here? -->
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\abs{\frac{1}{2}x+1}=\abs{\frac{1}{3}x+2}</m> breaks down into two pieces:
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{1}{2}x+1\amp=\frac{1}{3}x+2\amp\amp\text{or}\amp \frac{1}{2}x+1\amp=-\left(\frac{1}{3}x+2\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\frac{1}{2}x+1\amp=\frac{1}{3}x+2\amp\amp\text{or}\amp \frac{1}{2}x+1\amp=\highlight{-\frac{1}{3}x-2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\multiplyleft{6}\left(\frac{1}{2}x+1\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{6}\left(\frac{1}{3}x+2\right)\amp\amp\text{or}\amp \multiplyleft{6}\left(\frac{1}{2}x+1\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{6}\left(-\frac{1}{3}x-2\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x+6\amp=2x+12\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 3x+6\amp=-2x-12</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=6 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 5x\amp=-18</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=6 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-\frac{18}{5}</mrow>
                </md>
                So, the solution set is <m>\left\{6,-\frac{18}{5}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\abs{x-2}=\abs{x+1}</m> breaks down into two pieces:
                <md>
                  <mrow>x-2\amp=x+1\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-2\amp=-(x+1)</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-2\amp=x+1\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-2\amp=\highlight{-x-1}</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>x-2\addright{2}\subtractright{x}\amp=x+1\addright{2}\subtractright{x}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-2\addright{2}\addright{x}\amp=-x-1\addright{2}\addright{x}</mrow> -->
                  <mrow>x\amp=x+3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x\amp=1</mrow>
                  <mrow>0\amp=3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                Note that one of the two pieces gives us an equation with no solutions.
                Since <m>0\ne3</m>, we can safely ignore this piece.
                Thus the only solution is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
              </p>

              <p>
                We should visualize this equation graphically because our previous assumption was that two absolute value graphs would cross twice.
                The graph shows why there is only one crossing:
                the left and right sides of each <q>V</q> are parallel.
              </p>

              <sidebyside widths="47%">

                <image>
                  <description>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(x-2) and y=abs(x+1);y=abs(x-2) has its vertex at (2,0) with a slope of 1 on the right and -1 on the left;y=abs(x+1) has its vertex at (-1,0) with a slope of 1 on the right and -1 on the left;the V-shaped graphs cross at only one point (1/2,3/2)</description>

                  <latex-image>
                      <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                          \begin{axis}[xmin=-7, xmax=7, ymin=-2, ymax=7, xtick={-6,-5,...,6}, ytick={-1,0,...,6}]
                          \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(-7,6) (-1,0) (6,7)} node[pos=0.2, sloped, below]{$y=\abs{x+1}$};
                          \addplot[secondcurve] coordinates {(-5,7) (2,0) (7,5)} node[pos=0.8, sloped, above]{$y=\abs{x-2}$};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(.5, 1.5)};
                          \end{axis}
                      \end{tikzpicture}
                      ]]>
                  </latex-image>
                </image>

              </sidebyside>

            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\abs{x-1}=\abs{1-x}</m> breaks down into two pieces:
                <md>
                  <mrow>x-1\amp=1-x\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-1\amp=-(1-x)</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-1\amp=1-x\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-1\amp=\highlight{-1+x}</mrow>
            <!-- <mrow>\addleft{x}x-1\addright{1}\amp=\addleft{1}1-x\addright{x}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\subtractright{x}-1\addright{1}\amp=-1\addright{1}+x\subtractright{x}</mrow> -->
                  <mrow>2x\amp=2\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=0+x</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=1\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 0\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                Note that our second equation is an identity so recall from <xref ref="section-special-solution-sets">Section</xref>
                that the solution set is <q>all real numbers.</q>
              </p>

              <p>
                So, our two pieces have solutions <m>1</m> and
                <q>all real numbers.</q> Since <m>1</m> <em>is</em>
                a real number and we have an <em>or</em> statement,
                our overall solution set is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
                The graph confirms our answer since the two
                <q>V</q> graphs are coinciding.
              </p>

              <figure xml:id="figure-absolute-value-solving-part-ii-d">
                <caption><m>y=\abs{x-1}</m> and <m>y=\abs{1-x}</m></caption>
                <image width="47%">
                  <description>a Cartesian graph with the graphs of y=abs(x-1) and y=abs(1-x);y=abs(x-1) has its vertex at (1,0) with a slope of 1 on the right and -1 on the left;y=abs(1-x) has its vertex at (1,0) with a slope of 1 on the right and -1 on the left;the V-shaped graphs overlap everywhere so they are coinciding</description>

                    <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-7, xmax=7, ymin=-2, ymax=7, xtick={-6,-5,...,6}, ytick={-1,0,...,6},width=0.47\linewidth]
                            \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(-6,6.95) (1,-0.05) (7,5.95)} node[pos=0.3, sloped, below]{$y=\abs{x-1}$};
                            \addplot[secondcurve] coordinates {(-6,7) (1,0) (7,6)} node[pos=0.8, sloped, above]{$y=\abs{1-x}$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
              </figure>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

